WHAT MAKES A FACT GOOD (READ FIRST)
═══════════════════════════════════
The target is NOT "most obscure." The target is "makes a viewer say wait, WHAT?" — AND can be FRAMED as hidden, dark, or overlooked lore (the channel's signature angle).

Obscurity is allowed and welcome — but ONLY when it raises the reaction. A rare-but-boring fact is worse than a mid-rarity fascinating one.

The ideal fact pattern (the "soap pattern"):
A small, concrete, almost ordinary question (a texture, smell, sound, habit, weird detail) applied to a famous or central thing — where the real, canon answer is funnier, darker, or stranger than expected.

THE FRAMING LAYER (this channel's superpower):
Once you have the real detail, frame it the way this channel does — as something hidden, missed, or unsettling: "the disturbing reason," "the detail nobody noticed," "what this scene was really hiding," "the messed-up lore behind." The fact stays 100% real and un-exaggerated; the FRAMING is what turns a neat fact into a must-watch.

Reference example (from Jujutsu Kaisen, for calibration only — do NOT reuse unless [SERIES] is that show):
"Sukuna's severed finger feels and smells like soap." → famous object, hidden physical detail, canon, zero lore needed, instant 'wait WHAT?'. THIS is the level and flavor to aim for, applied to [SERIES].

NOTE: Even when anchored to a hot/hype topic, the fact must still follow the soap pattern — a concrete micro-detail with a strong framing, not a plot summary of the new episode.

